ense of belonging as they inhabit the interstices of several cultural-national formations—Panama, their nation of residence; China/Taiwan, their ethnic homeland; and the United States, the colonial force. Juxtaposing the concepts of diaspora and citizenship, this book offers an innovative framework to help us understand how diasporic subjects engage the politics of cultural and political belonging in a transnational context. It does so by examining the interaction between continually shifting geopolitical dynamics, as well as the maneuvers undertaken by diasporic people to negotiate and transform those conditions. In essence, this book explores the contingent citizenship experienced by diasporic Chinese and their efforts to imagine and construct "home" in diaspora.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aChinesexMigrationsxHistory. 0aChinesezForeign countriesxEthnic identity. 0aChinesezPanamaxEthnic identity. 0aChinesezPanamaxHistory. 0aGeopolitics. 0aNationalismxSocial aspects. 0aTransnationalism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476785940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804767859423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804767859/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles